g.addNativeRenderCallback(new NativeRenderCallback(){

    public void render(Pipeline pipeline){

        if ( IOS_OPENGL_ES_2.equals(pipeline) ){

            callSomeNativeMethodThatUsesOpenGLES2();

        }  else if ( IOS_CORE_GRAPHICS.equals(pipeline) ){

            callSomeNativeMethodThatUsesTheCoreGraphicsContext();
        }

    }
});
```

}

On the CodenameOne side of things, a NativeRenderCallback would either be wrapped in 
an executable op that is added to the pipeline (in the case of iOS), or, if the 
mode is immediate drawing (e.g. Android or IOS mutable image grahics drawing), the render() 
method would just be called immediately.

I realize that this gives use developers a lot of rope to hang ourselves, and modules
that depend on too many implementation details of the underlying port are subject to
break if the CN1 core is changed, but I think that it is worth the tradeoff.

Having this sort of access will make it much easier to add to CN1's graphics abilities 
incrementally.

If you are OK with this, I can make the changes myself.  It would only require adding a few lines of 
code in CodenameOne implementation and the iOS port.

Original [issue 1043](https://code.google.com/p/codenameone/issues/detail?id=1043) created by codenameone on 2014-01-17T19:10:50.000Z:

Currently the implementation of nextPowerOf2 on iOS calculates an extra power of 2.

Current implementation:
int nextPowerOf2(int val) {
    int i;
    for(i = 8 ; i &lt;= val ; i *= 2);
    return i;
}

e.g. nextPowerOf2(256)  produces 512

I suggest changing it to
int nextPowerOf2(int val) {
    int i;
    for(i = 8 ; i &lt; val ; i *= 2);
    return i;
}

That way if val is already a power of 2 we don't need to grow anymore.

