Original [issue 802](https://code.google.com/p/codenameone/issues/detail?id=802) created by codenameone on 2013-07-25T05:20:43.000Z:

The Android WebView needs an implementation of onGeolocatonPermissionsShowPrompt in order to enable the javascript location API to work in the WebBrowser component.  It does work in iPhone currently so it would be nice to make it work on Android too.

In addition to location permissions the following method of the WebChromeBrowser in the native WebView needs to be implemented to make it work.

A suggested implementation (and the relevant documentation) is pasted below, but I also would like to know if there is another approach that works.  For this particular app a certain chunk of the functionality is in a web browser and this is the last piece that isn't consistent across the devices we are using.  

Implementation:

```
    @Override
    public void onGeolocationPermissionsShowPrompt(String origin,
            GeolocationPermissions.Callback callback) {
        // Always grant permission since the app itself requires location
        // permission and the user has therefore already granted it
        callback.invoke(origin, true, false);
    }
```

Docs:

public synchronized void setGeolocationEnabled (boolean flag)

Added in API level 5
Sets whether Geolocation is enabled. The default is true.

Please note that in order for the Geolocation API to be usable by a page in the WebView, the following requirements must be met:

an application must have permission to access the device location, see ACCESS_COARSE_LOCATION, ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION;
an application must provide an implementation of the onGeolocationPermissionsShowPrompt(String, GeolocationPermissions.Callback) callback to receive notifications that a page is requesting access to location via the JavaScript Geolocation API.

