Original [issue 483](https://code.google.com/p/codenameone/issues/detail?id=483) created by codenameone on 2013-01-13T18:07:51.000Z:

The BrowserComponent.setURL() implementation is inconsistent across platforms for local URLs.  (My testing is currently limited to JavaSE, Android, and iOS).  Currently, on JavaSE and Android, requests for URLs with the jar: protocol are handled by the default setBrowserURL implementation (in the CodenameOneImplementation class) which uses the getResourceAsStream() to load the contents from the local file and then set the page contents using setPage().  On iOS, the setBrowserURL() implementation instead converts the jar:// url to the correct file:// URL for the requested file.  The iOS implementation is preferred to the default implementation because is allows resources to be included in the page via relative paths in a manner that is consistent with external web pages.

On android and JavaSE, resources that are included (e.g. images and scripts) in the page fail to load because the relative paths are not resolved correctly when using the setPage() method.  This despite the fact that the 2nd parameter of setPage() is being provided which should specify the base URL from with to resolve relative paths.  The reason they fail is because the JavaSE BrowserComponent simply ignores the 2nd parameter of setPage() as there doesn't seem to be an equivalent functionality that we can tap into in the JavaFX WebEngine.  On Android it is likely because it is having problems resolving jar: URLs in the web view (this may be fixable on its own by trying to tap into all resource requests and remapping them... currently requests for webpages seem to be intercepted and mapped correctly, but not for other resources).

This can be illustrated with the following example:

WebBrowser b = new WebBrowser();
b.setURL(&quot;jar:///ca/weblite/codename1/tests/AddAsync.html&quot;);

Where we have the ca/weblite/codename1/tests/AddAsync.html file with the contents:

&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;TODO write content&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;script src=&quot;AddAsync.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

And a the ca/weblite/codename1/tests/AddAsync.js file with contents:

document.writeln(&quot;In Add Async&quot;);

If we build and run this example, the &quot;In Add Async&quot; line appears only in the iOS version.  It does not appear in the Android version or the JavaSE version because it is not resolving the relative URL in the &lt;script&gt; tag.

I have attached a patch that changes the implementation of setBrowserURL() for the Android and JavaSE implementations with respect to jar: URLs so that relative resources are resolved correctly.

I have tested this on JavaSE (in the simulator) and Android 4.2.1 (Nexus 7) and it appears to work properly now.

-Steve

