Original [issue 326](https://code.google.com/p/codenameone/issues/detail?id=326) created by codenameone on 2012-09-12T22:14:16.000Z:

I spent some time going through the Android Port in-app billing code. Here all of the issues that I found with the in-app purchase implementation.

1) &quot;You must make all in-app billing requests from your application's main thread&quot;
(http://developer.android.com/guide/google/play/billing/billing_integrate.html)
Affected methods: 
CodenameOneActivity.restoreDatabase (call to billing.restoreTransactions())
CodenameOneActivity.purchase
CodenameOneActivity.subscribe

2) You may already be doing this, but from documentation:
(http://developer.android.com/guide/google/play/billing/billing_best_practices.html)
If you use Proguard to obfuscate your code, you must add the following line to your Proguard configuration file:
-keep class com.android.vending.billing.**

3) Consts.java: Consts.ACTION_CONFIRM_NOTIFICATION, Consts.ACTION_GET_PURCHASE_INFORMATION, Consts.ACTION_RESTORE_TRANSACTIONS
These constants are still set to the &quot;com.example.dungeons&quot; values, they should probably at the very least be unique to CN1 and best case different for every application. These constants are used in BillingService at line 380.

4)  Security.java at line 147 requires a public key.
There needs to be a way to provide the publisher public key or no purchase responses will be verified. Also, as per the online documentation, the string literal should NOT be included in the source. Instead it should be generated by possibly XORing 2 strings.

5) purchaseDB private field unnecessary in CodenameOneActivity.  CodenameOneActivity.doInitializeOwnedItems is the only method that uses the db. The database should be created at the beginning of doInitializeOwnedItems and closed at the end of the function. Having an instance database field open for the life of the activity is unnecessary. Furthermore, this is the approach taken by ResponseHandler.purchaseResponse.

6) ResponseHandler. purchaseResponse adds one to the quantity when purchase is refunded. However generous, this is incorrect. If this behavior is desired, it should be added by the app developer not by CN1.

Instead of:
if (state == PurchaseState.PURCHASED || state == PurchaseState.REFUNDED) {
    quantity += 1;
}

We should probably have:
if(state == PurchaseState.PURCHASED) {
    quantity += 1;
}
else if(state == PurchaseState.REFUNDED) {
    quantity -= 1;
}

7) Possible security issue related to storing the purchase info in the database. I believe that the product name (the sku) should be obfuscated before stored in the PurchaseDatabase instance. The importance that I see in this is that it prevents anyone from just simply copying the database file from one device to another or editing the database file to get free products.  The product name could obfuscated using the AESObfuscator class form the google play licensing code (I have attached the source for this) - this is of course just one way of doing this but probably the easiest.

The obfuscator uses a unique device id, the app package name, and a 20 random byte salt variable to obfuscate the values. The name of the product for each user is stored differently preventing copying or modification of the database file being able to spoof purchases. The name would need to be obfuscated in both database tables used in PurchaseDatabase and also used when reading the purchased items in CodenameOneActivity.doInitializeOwnedItems.  If this path is taken, there needs to be a way for the random 20 byte salt to be provided when sending an Android build. As long as the name is properly obfuscated it doesn’t matter if you choose the google licensing AESObfuscator or use something else.

8) Currently, BillingService.checkBillingSupported does not check if subscriptions are supported, only checks if regular in app purchases are supported. This is because BillingService.CheckBillingSupported class uses API version 1 when checking if in-app billinf is supported. To fix this, you need to alter the BillingService.CheckBillingSupported class to take a boolean in the constructor determining if it should check for subscriptions. In BillingService.CheckBillingSupported.run() it should pass this boolean to BillingService.makeRequestBundle.

This also requires a change to the CodenameOneActivity.CN1PurchaseObserver class. Basically, the first time you check if billing is supported, call billing.checkBillingSupported(true), which will check if subscriptions are supported. If this returns true (asynchronously), then both regular purchases and subscriptions are supported. However, if it returns false, then call billing.checkBillingSupported(false), which will check if regular in app purchases are supported only.

9) CodenameOneActivity.CN1PurchaseObserver.onPurchaseStateChange method does not take into account refunds. I recommend this code for the method:
public void onPurchaseStateChange(Consts.PurchaseState purchaseState, String itemId,
    int quantity, long purchaseTime, String developerPayload) {
    Object app = getApp();
    PurchaseCallback pc = app instanceof PurchaseCallback ? (PurchaseCallback)app : null;
    if (purchaseState == Consts.PurchaseState.PURCHASED) {
    if(pc != null) {
        pc.itemPurchased(itemId);
    }
    getOwnedItems().add(itemId);
    }
    else if (purchaseState == Consts.PurchaseState.REFUNDED){
    if(pc != null) {
        pc.itemRefunded(itemId);
    }
    if(quantity &lt;= 0) {
        getOwnedItems().remove(itemId);
    }
    }
}
This allows the PurchaseCallback.itemRefunded method to be called and removes the item from the ownedItems set when  the quantity is 0. 

10) This isn't specific issue with the code but something you may want to look into. I'm not sure how canceled subscriptions are handled in regards to the messages to the PurchaseObserver class. CN1PurchaseObserver.onPurchaseStateChange method may need to take into account the CANCELED state for subscriptions, but I'm not sure about this.

